questionTemplates.text:
M: Afternoon, Can I help you?
W: Good afternoon. I'd like to buy a coat.
{a}

M: Excuse me. Where would I find medicine for dogs?
W: We have some on aisle five. If you need a wider selection, however, I would suggest going to see an animal doctor.
{a}

W: I heard you got a full mark in math exam. Congratulations!
M: Thanks! I'm sure you also did a good job.
{a}

W: How can I get to the airport?
M: You can to there by subway, by bus, or by taxi. The subway is the quickest, but the bus is the cheapest.
{a}

W: Tomorrow is Saturday. Shall we go fishing?
M: Ok, but we must finish our homework first.
{a}

F: Sorry, Mr. Li. I'm late. The traffic is bad.
M: It doesn't matter.
{a}

W: Excuse me. Do you have the time?
M: Yes. It's 8: 45, but my watch is a little bit fast.
{a}

W: Hey Mark, have you been able to sell your old piano yet?
M: Oh, you were right, just posting notices on bulletin boards at a couple of supermarkets wasn't enough. I think I have to place an advertisement in the local newspaper.
{a}

W: Excuse me. Can you pass me the salt?
M: Certainly, here you are.
{a}

M: When do you have flights to Xianyang?
W: We have a flight at 10:45 am.
{a}

M: Excuse me. Do you know where the post office is?
W: Of course. Go to the corner and turn right. Walk one block and turn right again. The post office is on the corner.
{a}

F: How many students are there in Class 1?
M: Let me see. Twenty boys and twenty-five girls.
{a}

W: The sports meeting starts at 8:00.
M: In order to get a good seat, we must arrive there fifteen minutes in advance.
{a}

M: Good afternoon! I have an appointment with Dr. Jones.
W: Please take a seat. He will be with you in a few minutes.
{a}

M: Hi,Jane,it's been ages. You haven't changed a bit.
W: Except for the hair.
{a}

W: Why didn't your wife come here with you for dinner yesterday?
M: Oh, she just got back home from Korea yesterday and she was too tired to come. She also visited Japan, Singapore and Malaysia.
{a}

M: I think it's about time we made a move.
W: What? Won't you have another coffee?
{a}

W: Excuse me, visiting hours are over. It's time for you to leave.
M: I'm sorry, I didn't know the time or I would have left earlier.
{a}

M: I wish we had taken an umbrella.
W: That's my fault. I thought it wouldn't rain today.
{a}

W: Did you see my book? It's not on the shelf, nor on my desk.
M: Why don't you look under your chair? That's where I saw it a little while ago. Maybe it just fell when you went to the kitchen.
{a}

M: What's in that bag over there?
W: I bought some apples, peaches, pears and grapes.
{a}

M: What a waste of money just for a new arts center! Why couldn't the money be spent on something more important?
W: Nonsense! Nothing is more important than the arts.
{a}

W: Nobody told me that Bill was in the hospital.
M: Sorry. I meant to give you a call when I found out but it slipped my mind.
{a}

W: It is a good film, isn't it?
M: It was, wasn't it!
{a}

M: Do you want to eat out tonight or would you rather eat at home?
W: We've eaten out a lot this week. I'm perfectly happy to stay home for a change-as long as I don't have to cook.
{a}
